      "side": 1,
      "message": "Potentially radical idea (as with all my feedback, you can say \"no\"). Inspired by https://dave.cheney.net/2017/06/11/go-without-package-scoped-variables and https://dave.cheney.net/2016/04/07/constant-errors whose blog I\u0027ve been reading a lot of lately\n\ntype Instance interface {\n  Instance() string // something uniqueish to avoid accidental implementation\n}\n\ntype PublicInstance interface {\n  IsPublic()\n}\n\ntype instance struct {\n name string\n}\n\nfunc (in *instance) Instance() string {\n return in.name\n}\n\nfunc (in *instance) String() string { // by implementing String(), we can simply use %v in format strings instead of having to do fmt.Sprintf(\"foo-%s-bar\", in.Instance())\n return in.name\n}\n\ntype publicInstance struct {\n name string\n}\n\nfunc (in *publicInstance) Instance() string {\n return in.name\n}\n\nfunc (in *publicInstance) String() string {\n return in.name\n}\n\nfunc (in *publicInstance) IsPublic() {}\n\nconst ChromeGPU  \u003d instance{\"chrome-gpu\"}\n//...\nconst SkiaPublic \u003d publicInstance{\"skia-public\"}\n\n\nOnce we have that, instead of \nif isPublicInstance(foo) {\n //...\n}\n\nWe can do\nif _, ok :\u003d foo.(PublicInstance); ok {\n  //...\n}\n\nPros:\nNo package level variable of instances (that could be mutated or forgotten about)\nWhen we create the variable, it is clear that it\u0027s a \"publicInstance\".\n\nCons: \nNot a simple string anymore, which could complicate other logic\n\n\nAs always, happy to discuss this in person.",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 10,
        "startChar": 12,
        "endLine": 10,
        "endChar": 20
      },
